SSH Keys – What They Are

SSH = Secure Shell

Secure – the connection is encrypted, so anyone intercepting the traffic can’t read the data.
Shell – a command‑line interface (the “shell”) that lets you run commands on a remote computer 
as if you were sitting in front of it.

In practice, SSH lets your Mac authenticate to GitHub (or any other server) using a cryptographic key pair, 
so you can push/pull code without sending passwords over the network.

The Problem Without SSH
When you push or pull from a remote repository (e.g., git@github.com:user/repo.git), 
Git needs to authenticate you. The naïve way is to send your GitHub username + password each time. 

That’s:

insecure (password travels over the network)
inconvenient (you’d have to type it for every push/pull)
The Solution: Public‑Key Cryptography
You generate a key pair on your Mac:

Private key – ~/.ssh/id_ed25519 (kept secret on your computer)
Public key – ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub (you can share safely)
You upload the public key to GitHub (Settings → SSH and GPG keys).

When you run git push or git clone over SSH, GitHub does this:

Sends a challenge (random data) to your Mac.
Your ssh client signs that challenge with the private key.
GitHub verifies the signature using the public key it already knows belongs to you.
If the verification succeeds, you’re authenticated without ever sending a password.

Benefits
Benefit	Explanation
Security	Private key never leaves your machine; the public key is harmless on its own.
Convenience	After the first setup, git push/pull works with no password prompts 
(unless you set a passphrase on the key).
Automation	Scripts, CI pipelines, and IDEs can push/pull without interactive log‑ins.
